## Trigger

```json
{
  "activation": {
    "anyPhrases": [
      "add a task",
      "create a task",
      "track this task",
      "task status",
      "mark this done",
      "block this task",
      "what tasks do we have"
    ]
  },
  "movement": {
    "target": "desk",
    "skipIfAlreadyThere": true
  }
}
```

Also use this skill even when those exact phrases are absent if the latest user message is an actionable work request. If the user asks the agent to do something, that request must become a task before the agent proceeds.

## Storage location

The authoritative store lives under the **claude-task-manager** project (not in this repo):

- `data/__PROJECT_ID__/tasks.json` ÔÇö the Kanban board (source of truth for tasks).
- `data/__PROJECT_ID__/context.json` ÔÇö the **user context** (source of truth for the user's intent, decisions, and init prompt; see "User context" below).

NEVER read/write these files directly from this project ÔÇö always go through the `task.sh`
wrapper below (it resolves the correct data directory).

## Token-efficient CLI (`task.sh`) ÔÇö THE ONLY WRITER

For handling `tasks.json`, **do not** re-read/rewrite the whole file (it costs a lot of
tokens). Use the `task.sh` wrapper bundled with the skill (jq-based), which produces
compact output and writes atomically (it automatically maintains the timestamp and
history/notes entries). The script is on the Claude settings allowlist and can run
without a permission prompt.

> **HARD RULE ÔÇö NEVER edit the JSON directly; only use `task.sh`.** Do not modify either
> `tasks.json` or `context.json` with the `Write`/`Edit` tools, and do not write back "the
> full JSON" by hand. Every mutation (both task AND context) must go **exclusively**
> through `task.sh` commands ÔÇö this way there is a single atomic writer, with consistent
> timestamps and history, and no corrupted/duplicated state. This applies to the **main
> agent and EVERY subagent/teammate**. For reads, use `task.sh`'s query commands
> (`summary`, `list`, `get`, `ctx` ÔÇª); only use `Read` on the JSON as a last resort, and
> never to write. (For `context.json`, use the `ctx-*` commands ÔÇö see below.)

> **If `task.sh` fails with `Permission denied` / `Could not open file ÔÇª tasks.json`:** the
> board's data files are owned by `root` (a container that ran as root wrote them ÔÇö happens on
> native Linux Docker). The file is `-rw-------` root:root, so the host user can neither read
> nor write it, and `task.sh` itself dies at the `jq` read ÔÇö this is NOT fixable by writing
> the JSON directly (that fails too). Ask the user to run **`ctm fix-perms`** (reclaims
> ownership; no `sudo` needed while the board is up), then retry. A restarted board (`ctm up`)
> keeps running as the host user, so it won't reoccur.

Canonical calling form (with the FULL absolute path, from any working directory):

```
__TASK_SH_PATH__ <command> [args] --as <agent>
```

> **REQUIRED: `--as <agent>` on every non-meta command.** Add your own name to every
> `task.sh` call: the **main agent uses `--as main`**, a teammate uses its own label
> (`--as backend-auth`). This is recorded as the `by` field on every event. Without
> `--as`, non-meta commands **throw an error**. Exceptions (no `--as` needed): `help`,
> `inbox`, `init`, `validate`, `restore`, `raw`.

> **No permission prompt needed ÔÇö call it DIRECTLY, as a bare command.** ALWAYS call
> `task.sh` with the absolute path above, as a **standalone** command ÔÇö no `cd`,
> `&&`/`||`, redirects (`2>&1`), or `$VARIABLE`. Claude Code requires a permission
> prompt for chained commands **segment by segment**, so a `cd ÔÇª && ÔÇªtask.sh ÔÇª` form
> would trigger a prompt. The script already has `TM_DIR` baked into itself (see
> `claude-task-manager/engine/projects.sh`), so `cd` is unnecessary anyway. The script
> is on the project allowlist (`.claude/settings.local.json`, `Bash(ÔÇªtask.sh:*)`), so
> the bare absolute call runs without a permission prompt.

Most common commands (always call with the FULL absolute path ÔÇö copy it as shown):

- `__TASK_SH_PATH__ summary --as main` ÔÇö counts by status (a quick "where do we stand" overview).
- `__TASK_SH_PATH__ list [status] --as main` ÔÇö compact list in `id [status] title` form.
- `__TASK_SH_PATH__ get <id> --as main` ÔÇö the full JSON of a SINGLE task (not the whole file).
- `__TASK_SH_PATH__ add <id> <title> [desc] --as main` ÔÇö a new task with `todo` status, with all required fields.
- `__TASK_SH_PATH__ status <id> <status> [note] --as main` ÔÇö status change + history entry.
- `__TASK_SH_PATH__ note <id> <text> --as main` ÔÇö append a note. Start it with an ALL-CAPS
  keyword + `:` and the board shows a colored phase badge on the note (and on the card): e.g.
  `RESEARCH`/`KUTAT├üS`, `PLAN`/`TERV`, `DECISION`/`D├ûNT├ëS`, `IMPL`/`FIX`/`REFACTOR`,
  `DONE`/`K├ëSZ`, `BLOCK`/`BLOKK`, `WARNING`/`FIGYELEM`, `VERIFIED`/`TEST`, `USER`, `HANDOFF`.
  Free text works too (neutral badge) ÔÇö the keyword is what makes a long note scannable.
- `__TASK_SH_PATH__ set <id> <field> <json-value> --as main` ÔÇö set an arbitrary field (quote strings like `'"main"'`).
- `__TASK_SH_PATH__ find <text> --as main` ÔÇö and likewise: `ÔÇª history <id>`, `ÔÇª ids`, `ÔÇª archive|unarchive|rm <id>`.

**Structured fields and workflow commands** (instead of encoding them into title/notes text):

- `ÔÇª priority <id> <low|normal|high|urgent>` ÔÇö priority (drives `next` ordering; note `list` is NOT priority-sorted).
- `ÔÇª tag <id> <add|rm> <tag>` ÔÇö tags (e.g. `frontend`/`backend`/`test`).
- `ÔÇª module <id> <area>` ÔÇö functional-area label (`assignedModule`), e.g. `event-edit`/`billing`; free text, empty string clears it. A separate axis from the work-type `tag`; filter with `list --module <area>`.
- `ÔÇª assign <id> <agent>` ÔÇö sets `assignedAgentId` (more convenient than `set` for claiming). For the base roster the identity IS the launch name; for a `tm-*` agent use the **stripped identity** (without the `tm-` prefix), not the launch name.
- `ÔÇª claim <id>` ÔÇö **atomic, race-safe** take: flips a `todo` to `in_progress` AND assigns it to the `--as` caller in one locked write; refuses if another agent already claimed it (prevents two agents double-working the same task). Teammates use this to pick up work.
- `ÔÇª handoff <id> <to> [note]` ÔÇö reassign to `<to>` AND send them a **directed** inbox ping (`ÔÇ╝´©Å`). The explicit way to route a finding/bug/sub-task to another teammate.
- `ÔÇª review <id> [reviewer=main] [note]` ÔÇö move to `review` AND route it to a reviewer (assigns them + pings their inbox), so review has an owner instead of silting up. Teammates close their part with this instead of a bare `status ÔÇª review`.
- `ÔÇª review-queue [reviewer]` ÔÇö tasks in `review` (oldest first) with age; optionally just one reviewer's queue. Main's "what's waiting for my sign-off" view.
- `ÔÇª stale [--older-than 24h] [status...]` ÔÇö held-but-idle tasks (default `in_progress`+`review`) past a threshold, by `lastActivityAt`. Surfaces stuck/forgotten work to re-route.
- `ÔÇª files <id> [add|rm <abs-path>...]` ÔÇö the source files a task touches (absolute paths, unique; no sub-op lists them). A standard duty on every task ÔÇö the machine-readable pointer to the change, kept out of the free-text note.
- `ÔÇª checklist <id> [add <text>...|done <item-id>...|undo <item-id>...|rm <item-id>...]` ÔÇö the small steps INSIDE a task (no sub-op lists them). **You (main) write the items; teammates only tick them off** ÔÇö see the workflow below. Items get a stable `c<n>` id, never reused. Use it for steps that don't deserve their own task ÔÇö a real sub-task belongs in `dep`/`handoff` instead. Marking a task `done` with unchecked items warns but doesn't block; ticking the last item does NOT change the status by itself. **Phrase every item as a short SENTENCE, never a one/two-word label** ÔÇö "add the `/discount` route to the checkout API", not "route". A teammate (especially a junior ÔÇö see the roster section) has to act on the item without asking you what it meant.
- `ÔÇª dep <id> <add|rm> <other-id>` ÔÇö dependency (`dependsOn`): `id` waits on `other-id`; includes cycle and existence checks.
- `ÔÇª deps <id>` ÔÇö what this task is waiting on and what it blocks.
- `ÔÇª next [--claim]` ÔÇö the next recommended `todo` task (no open dependency), sorted by priority. `--claim` atomically takes it (see `claim`).
- `ÔÇª list [status] --tag <t> --agent <a> --priority <p> --module <m> --all --json` ÔÇö filtered/machine-readable list.
- `ÔÇª status-many <status> <id...>` ÔÇö move multiple tasks to one status in a SINGLE atomic write.
- `ÔÇª reopen <id> [status]` ÔÇö reopen a closed/archived task.
- `ÔÇª validate` ÔÇö schema check (required fields, status, priority, broken dependencies, duplicate ids).
- `ÔÇª restore` ÔÇö restore the most recent pre-write backup (`tasks.json.bak`).
- `ÔÇª inbox <agent>` ÔÇö events generated by OTHER agents since `<agent>`'s cursor (meta command, no `--as`).

Full help: `__TASK_SH_PATH__ help`. Only read the full JSON (`ÔÇª raw` / Read) if the task
cannot be accomplished with the commands above.

## User context (session continuity)

Beyond individual tasks, maintain a durable **user context** so that work can be resumed in a
**fresh session** without re-interviewing the user. Store it (via `task.sh`'s `ctx-*`
commands) ÔÇö never with `Write`/`Edit`:

- Session starts and the file is missing ÔåÆ `ctx-init "<initPrompt>" "<goal>" --as main`.
- The user makes a **decision** ÔåÆ `ctx-decision "<topic>" "<decision>" "<rationale>" --as main`.
- A permanent rule/constraint is stated ÔåÆ `ctx-constraint "<text>" --as main`.
- An open question arises / is resolved ÔåÆ `ctx-question add|rm "<text>" --as main`.
- The active focus changes ÔåÆ `ctx-set currentFocus '"<task-id or text>"' --as main`.

At the start of every session, **read `__TASK_SH_PATH__ ctx` first**, and let it guide the work.

## Roles ÔÇö the main agent coordinates, teammates execute

The **main agent does NOT do the implementation work itself.** Its job is to capture and
break down requests into tasks, `add`/`assign` them, coordinate, review, and decide the
handoff ÔÇö it does **not** write the code/dev work directly. All actual implementation and
follow-up work is **delegated to teammate subagents** ÔÇö the project's base roster agents (and
`tm-*` agents where present). The main agent only: plans, adds/assigns tasks, reviews the
result, and decides the `review ÔåÆ done | assign+todo` handoff.

- When a request is actionable, `main` creates the task(s) and **assigns** them to the
  appropriate teammate (`ÔÇª assign <id> <agent> --as main`) instead of starting to implement.
- Each teammate claims its task, moves it to `in_progress`, does the work, and updates
  status with its own `--as <name>` (never `--as main`).
- `main` stays the coordinator across the whole loop: fill teammate queues, keep tasks
  assigned, and on `review` decide `done` or reassign.
- **Assign before anything can happen.** A teammate can only claim a task that is **assigned
  to it by name** ÔÇö `task.sh` refuses a claim on a task belonging to somebody else *or to
  nobody*. There is no tag-based self-service: an unassigned task sits still forever. Routing
  is main's job, and only main's.
- **Model choice is the LEVEL, not a launch flag.** Do NOT pass the Agent `model` parameter
  when launching a teammate ÔÇö pick the right *agent* instead and let its frontmatter decide.
  The dev roster is tiered, and the tier IS the model: `junior` = `haiku`, `medior` = `sonnet`,
  `senior` = `opus`. **Never use `fable`/`claude-fable-5`.**

### Teammate roster ÔÇö the base set

For the base agents the **launch name (`subagent_type`) and the task-manager identity
(`assign` / `--as`) are the SAME string** ÔÇö there is nothing to strip or translate:

| Agent | Model | Use it for |
|---|---|---|
| `ctm-be-junior` / `ctm-fe-junior` | haiku  | pre-broken-down, mechanical work ÔÇö see the rule below |
| `ctm-be-medior` / `ctm-fe-medior` | sonnet | **the default.** Features, refactors, real bugfixes |
| `ctm-be-senior` / `ctm-fe-senior` | opus   | architecture, contracts, escalation ÔÇö **needs permission** |
| `ctm-investigator`      | sonnet | read-only code investigation; usually first in the chain |
| `ctm-playwright-tester` | sonnet | verifying behavior in a real browser; usually last in the chain |

**Pick the level by the weight of the task, and when unsure pick the medior.** It is the
workhorse: unless a task is trivially mechanical or genuinely architectural, it belongs there.

**The senior (`opus`) needs the user's explicit permission ÔÇö ASK BEFORE LAUNCHING IT.** It is
the most expensive agent in the roster, so it is not yours to start on your own judgement. If
the user says no, or you can't ask, **the medior does the work** ÔÇö never stall a task on a
senior you weren't allowed to launch. If the medior then blocks on an architectural decision,
bring that decision to the user yourself.

**The junior only works from a breakdown.** It runs on the cheapest model and will bounce back
anything it has to think about. Only assign it a task that already has a **checklist and named
files** ÔÇö which means *you* (or the senior) must break it down first. That breakdown costs
something, so the junior only pays off on bulk, repetitive, decided work. **If you find
yourself about to write a breakdown just to justify using the junior, give it to the medior.**

**Area handoffs happen medior-to-medior** (`ctm-be-medior` Ôåö `ctm-fe-medior`), never diagonally
across levels.

**`ctm-playwright-tester` is environment-dependent:** it can only do its job where the Playwright
MCP server is available. If it isn't, don't launch it ÔÇö do the verification yourself, or hand
it to the human, and say which it was. Never let a task pass as "verified" because the agent
that would have checked it couldn't run.

### Who reviews the junior

By default **the junior routes its work to you (`main`)**, and you close it. You may instead
delegate that review to the medior ÔÇö it saves your context on a run of many small junior tasks,
at the cost of you seeing less. **That delegation needs the user's explicit permission.** With
it:

- Tell **both** agents in the task/instruction: the junior routes to `<be|fe>-medior`, and the
  medior knows it may close that task as `done`.
- Without a word from you, the junior defaults to `main` ÔÇö forgetting to mention it is safe,
  it just falls back.

A teammate **never** closes its own task as `done`; that stays your call.

The project may also ship `tm-*` variants ÔÇö their identity is the name WITHOUT the `tm-`
prefix (e.g. `tm-frontend` ÔåÆ `frontend`), so check the `--as` line inside each `tm-*` agent
before assigning. **Watch for identity collisions:** two agents that claim tasks under the same
`--as` name will fight over the same queue. `ctm agent add` refuses the base names for exactly
this reason, but a hand-written agent definition can still collide ÔÇö if a task keeps getting
picked up by the wrong teammate, that's the first thing to check.

### How many teammates to run

**Run 3-4 teammates at a time ÔÇö no more ÔÇö and keep feeding them.** The roster has eight
definitions; that is a menu, NOT a launch list. The right default is `ctm-be-medior`, `ctm-fe-medior`,
`ctm-investigator`, plus a fourth as the work demands (`ctm-playwright-tester` where the environment
allows it, or one junior/senior ÔÇö not both). This is a limit on CONCURRENCY, not on total work:
a teammate that finishes its task stays alive and takes the next one.

- **Never run two levels of the same area at once** unless the work genuinely splits that way
  (e.g. the senior designs while the junior grinds a decided list). A `ctm-be-junior` and a
  `ctm-be-medior` racing on the same feature is coordination cost with no throughput gain.

- **Don't stop a teammate to start another.** Spawning is expensive and throws away everything
  it has learned about the codebase. Send it the next task instead.
- **Feed them, don't batch them.** When a teammate reports back, give it the next task right
  away rather than waiting for the others to finish. A blocked teammate is idle capacity.
- **More than 4 in parallel ONLY if the user asks for it.** Beyond that the coordination cost
  (routing, review, merge conflicts on the same files) grows faster than the throughput, and
  two teammates editing the same file will undo each other's work.
- **Fewer is fine.** If the work is one-dimensional, one teammate is the right number ÔÇö don't
  spawn an `ctm-fe-medior` for a task with no frontend in it.

## Required workflow

Every step goes through `task.sh` (never a direct JSON write). **Add `--as main` to
every non-meta command** (as the main agent); a teammate uses its own `--as <name>`:

1. Before handling an actionable request, `__TASK_SH_PATH__ summary --as main` / `list ÔÇª --as main`.
2. At session start, `__TASK_SH_PATH__ ctx --as main`; if missing, `ctx-init "<initPrompt>" "<goal>" --as main`.
3. If the last user message is actionable and there's no active task for it, immediately `__TASK_SH_PATH__ add <id> "<title>" "<desc>" --as main`. On add, set **priority** only when it isn't ordinary ÔÇö `ÔÇª priority <id> high|urgent --as main` for blockers or user-flagged urgency (`normal` is the default; don't set it explicitly). This is what makes a teammate's `next` pick the right task first. Optionally label the **functional area** with `ÔÇª module <id> <area> --as main` when filtering the board by area (`list --module <area>`) is useful ÔÇö a separate axis from the `frontend`/`backend` work-type tags.
4. **When the task breaks into steps, record them as a checklist ON the task ÔÇö this is main's job, not the teammate's.** You are the one who planned the work; a teammate that has to invent the steps has already lost the plan. Write them at `add` time (or as soon as the breakdown is clear), and the teammate then just ticks them off as it goes, so progress is visible while the work is running rather than only in the closing note. Keep the boundary: a step that needs its own owner or status is a TASK (`add` + `handoff`), not a checklist item.
   `__TASK_SH_PATH__ checklist <id> add "extend the save service to accept the new field" "add the /discount route to the API" "wire the discount field into the checkout form" --as main`
5. Before starting work, the task should be `todo`, or run `__TASK_SH_PATH__ status <id> in_progress --as main`.
6. If the work cannot proceed, `__TASK_SH_PATH__ status <id> blocked "<reason>" --as main`.
7. When done, `__TASK_SH_PATH__ status <id> done --as main`. With unchecked checklist items left, this warns on stderr but still goes through ÔÇö either tick them, remove the ones that turned out unnecessary, or accept the warning knowingly.
8. If user review/confirmation is needed, `__TASK_SH_PATH__ status <id> review --as main`.
9. `task.sh` writes every mutation atomically and maintains the timestamp/history ÔÇö manually
   writing back the full JSON is unnecessary and forbidden.

## Status rules

- New actionable requests start as `todo` unless work has already begun.
- Move to `in_progress` when the agent is actively working.
- Move to `blocked` when progress depends on missing input, credentials, approvals, or failures.
- Move to `review` when the work is ready for inspection or handoff.
- Move to `done` only when the requested work is complete.

## Board (shared, dockerized interface)

The board is served by the **claude-task-manager** project (docker compose, port 3333),
a **shared** interface for all installed projects ÔÇö select this project
(**__PROJECT_LABEL__**) from the "Source" picker in the header:

```
cd /Users/mgeri1993/code/projects/claude-task-manager && docker compose up -d
# then: http://localhost:3333/
```

Writes from the board **still go through `task.sh`** (the single-writer invariant is
preserved: atomic lock, history, `events.jsonl`, inbox) ÔÇö the browser NEVER writes the
JSON directly. `task.sh` calls (agent work) **don't need docker** ÔÇö the
`__TASK_SH_PATH__` above is a plain host bash script that runs standalone.

